AGREEMENT FOR PARTIAL REQUIREMENTSWHOLESALE ELECTRIC SERVICE This AGREEMENT FOR PARTIAL REQUIREMENTS WHOLESALE ELECTRIC SERVICE (this "Agreement") dated as of August 1, 2011 (the "Execution Date"), is entered into between SAM RAYBURN MUNICIPAL POWER AGENCY, a political subdivision of the State of Texas ("SRMPA"), and ENTERGY GULF STATES LOUISIANA, L.L.C., a limited liability company organized and existing under the laws of the State of Louisiana ("EGSL"). SRMPA and EGSL are sometimes referred to herein individually as a "Party" or collectively as the "Parties". WHEREAS, SRMPA desires to purchase, and EGSL desires to sell, the Partial Requirements Capacity and the Partial Requirements Energy (each as defined below) for each hour of the Delivery Period (as defined below). NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the undertakings and subject to the conditions set forth herein, the Parties agree as follows: DEFINED TERMS AND INTERPRETATION Defined Terms. As used in this Agreement, the following terms shall have the following meanings: “Accepted Electrical Practices” means those practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric power generation industry in the Gulf Coast region of the United States of America during the relevant time period or any of the practices, methods, and acts that, in the exercise of reasonable judgment and in light of the facts known at the time a decision is made, could have been expected to accomplish a desired result at reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety, and expedition. Accepted Electrical Practices are not intended to be limited to the optimum practices, methods, or acts to the exclusion of others, but rather to those practices, methods, and acts generally engaged in or approved in the Gulf Coast region of the United States of America during the relevant time period or which could have reasonably been expected to accomplish a desired result, as described in the immediately preceding sentence. "Affected Party" has the meaning set forth in Section 12.1. "Affiliate" means any Person which, directly or indirectly, controls, or is controlled by, or is under common control with, another Person and any partner, officer or employee of any such Persons. For purposes of this definition, control shall mean the power, directly or indirectly, to direct or in effect cause the direction of the management and policies of such Person whether by contract or otherwise. "Agreement" has the meaning set forth in the preamble. "Approvals" means all approvals, permits, licenses, consents, waivers or other authorizations from, notifications to, or filings or registrations with, Governmental Authorities or other third parties. "Balancing Authority" means the Person(s) responsible for integrating resource plans and maintaining load-interchange-generation balance within a Balancing Authority Area. As of the Effective Date, Entergy Electric System is the Balancing Authority in respect of the Balancing Authority Area that includes the Delivery Points and the Network Resource Delivery Points.
"Balancing Authority Area" means an electric power system or combination of electric power systems to which a common automatic generation control scheme is applied in order to: (i) match, at all times, the power output of the generators within such electric power system(s) and the net power purchased from or sold to Persons outside such electric power system(s), with the load within such electric power system(s); (ii) maintain scheduled interchange with other such electric power system(s), within the limits of Accepted Electrical Practices; (iii) maintain the frequency of such electric power system(s) within reasonable limits in accordance with Accepted Electrical Practices; and (iv) provide sufficient generating capacity to maintain operating reserves in accordance with Accepted Electrical Practices.
"Bankrupt" means, with respect to any entity, such entity (i) files a petition or otherwise commences, authorizes or acquiesces in the commencement of a proceeding or cause of action under any bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization, or similar law, or has any such petition filed or commenced against it and with respect to any such petition filed or commenced against it, such petition remains in effect for thirty (30) or more days, (ii) makes an assignment or any general arrangement for the benefit of creditors, (iii) otherwise becomes bankrupt or insolvent (however evidenced), (iv) has a liquidator, administrator, receiver, trustee, conservator, or similar official appointed with respect to it or any substantial portion of its property or assets, or (v) is generally unable to pay its debts as they fall due. "SRMPA Overpayment" shall have the meaning set forth in Section 3.3(b). TERM AND DELIVERY PERIOD; CONDITIONS PRECEDENT Term. The term of this Agreement (the "Term") shall commence on the Execution Date and shall continue in effect until the earlier of (i) midnight CPT (end of hour ending 2400) on December 31, 2035; (ii) the termination of the Nelson IP Retail Load Assignment; or (iii) the earlier termination of this Agreement in accordance with the terms hereof (the earliest of such dates being the "Termination Date"); provided, however, that such termination shall not affect or excuse (A) the performance of either Party under any provisions of this Agreement that by its terms survives any such termination or (B) the rights and obligations of the Parties that accrue prior or upon such termination. Delivery Period. Subject to Sections 2.3 and 2.4, EGSL's obligation to sell and deliver the Partial Requirements Energy and Partial Requirements Capacity, and SRMPA's obligation to purchase the Partial Requirements Energy and Partial Requirements Capacity, pursuant to Articles 3 and 4 shall commence at midnight CPT (beginning of hour ending 0100) on the Delivery Period Commencement Date, and continue through and including midnight CPT (end of hour ending 2400) on the Termination Date (such period being the "Delivery Period"). SRMPA's Conditions Precedent. Subject to Section 2.5, the commencement of the Delivery Period and the obligation of SRMPA to commence paying the Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge, the Monthly Partial Requirements Energy Charge and the transmission service charges shall be subject to the fulfillment of each of the following conditions, except to the extent SRMPA waives the fulfillment of such condition in writing: the condition precedent set forth in Section 2.4(a) shall have been satisfied or waived by EGSL by December 1, 2011; the representations and warranties of EGSL set forth in this Agreement shall be true and correct in all material respects, on and as of the Execution Date and the Delivery Period Commencement Date, except to the extent that such representations and warranties by their term speak as of a date earlier than the Delivery Period Commencement Date, in which case they shall be true and correct as of such date and SRMPA shall have received a certificate from EGSL, executed on its behalf by an authorized officer, dated as of the Delivery Period Commencement Date certifying the same; and on or before ninety days after the Execution Date, SRMPA Resources with an aggregate capacity of at least 225 MW shall have been qualified as, and shall be, "Network Resources" of SRMPA under the Entergy OATT. EGSL's Conditions Precedent. Subject to Section 2.5, the commencement of the Delivery Period and the obligation of EGSL to commence performance of its obligations under Article 3 (Partial Requirements Capacity), Article 4 (Partial Requirements Energy), Article 7 (Transmission), Article 9 (Metering) and Article 11 (Billing and Payment) of this Agreement shall be subject to the fulfillment of each of the following conditions, except to the extent EGSL waives the fulfillment of such condition in writing in its sole and absolute discretion: EGSL shall have obtained, on or before December 1, 2011, all Approvals advisable or necessary for EGSL to perform its obligations under this Agreement and such Approvals shall have been granted or issued on terms or conditions satisfactory to EGSL in its sole and absolute discretion; the representations and warranties of SRMPA set forth in this Agreement shall be true and correct in all material respects, on and as of the Execution Date and the Delivery Period Commencement Date, except to the extent that such representations and warranties by their term speak as of a date earlier than the Delivery Period Commencement Date, in which case they shall be true and correct as of such date and EGSL shall have received a certificate from SRMPA, executed on its behalf by an authorized officer, dated as of the Delivery Period Commencement Date certifying the same; and the Original Partial Requirements Agreement shall have been suspended effective as of the Delivery Period Commencement Date pursuant to a suspension and mutual release agreement in form and substance satisfactory to EGSL. Efforts to Fulfill Conditions. Commencing on the Execution Date, and subject to the other terms and conditions of this Agreement, SRMPA and EGSL each shall use commercially reasonable efforts to take, or cause to be taken, all appropriate action, and do, or cause to be done, and assist and cooperate with the other in taking or doing, all things necessary, proper or advisable to cause the fulfillment of the respective conditions set forth in Sections 2.3 and 2.4. In furtherance of the foregoing, EGSL agrees to file, or cause to be filed, all notifications and filings required to be filed with respect to this Agreement with FERC on or before September 1, 2011. For the avoidance of doubt, nothing in this Agreement shall require EGSL to offer or accept any limitation, condition, or term on or related to any of its Approvals that is unsatisfactory or unacceptable to EGSL in its sole and absolute discretion. SRMPA's obligation to cooperate with and assist EGSL as provided above shall include the obligation (i) to support fully this Agreement and the terms hereof in any regulatory or similar proceeding, case, action or investigation whenever occurring after the Execution Date, including in any hearing, discovery or filing, involving a Governmental Approval of or relating to this Agreement or any of the terms hereof, and (ii) not to take any action or position or make any claim in any such proceeding, case, action or investigation that is inconsistent with the foregoing. For the avoidance of doubt, SRMPA shall not have any obligation to intervene in any proceeding, case or action pending involving a Governmental Approval of, or relating to, this Agreement, even if requested to do so by EGSL pursuant to this Section 2.5(a). EGSL may, among other things, submit this Agreement to the Governmental Authority having jurisdiction over the retail operations of EGSL, together with an application for approval of this Agreement, and/or request rate recovery of the costs associated with its participation in this Agreement based on a finding that such participation is prudent. This Agreement may be terminated by: SRMPA, upon written notice to EGSL as provided herein, in the event that any condition set forth in Section 2.3 is not satisfied or waived by SRMPA in accordance with such Section; or EGSL, upon written notice to SRMPA as provided herein, in the event that any condition set forth in Section 2.4 is not satisfied or waived by EGSL in accordance with such Section; provided, however, that neither Party may terminate this Agreement pursuant to this Section 2.6 if (i) such Party’s failure to fulfill its obligations with respect to Section 2.5 shall be the primary reason that such condition shall not have been satisfied or (ii) the condition giving rise to such Party's right of termination has been satisfied or waived prior to the exercise of such termination right. A termination of this Agreement in accordance with this Section 2.6 shall be without penalty or liability to either Party arising out of such termination. Additional Termination Events. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, either Party may, upon written notice to the other Party as provided herein, terminate this Agreement if this Agreement and the transactions contemplated hereby are a subject of a regulatory proceeding, and in such proceeding, a Governmental Authority (excluding SRMPA, the Vinton Public Power Authority, and the Cities of Liberty, Livingston, and Jasper, Texas, and any other Person that becomes a member of SRMPA) takes an action (including setting and/or scheduling a matter for hearing) or fails to take an action that such Party, in its sole and absolute discretion, determines to have an adverse impact on such Party, its shareholders or its ratepayers; provided, however, that neither Party may terminate this Agreement pursuant to this Section 2.7 if such Party’s acts or omissions are the primary reason giving rise to such termination right. A termination of this Agreement in accordance with this Section 2.7 shall be without penalty or liability to either Party arising out of such termination.
PARTIAL REQUIREMENTS CAPACITY Partial Requirements Capacity. Each calendar month during the Delivery Period, EGSL shall provide, or cause to be provided, to SRMPA, and SRMPA shall purchase from EGSL, the Partial Requirements Capacity for such calendar month determined in accordance with the following calculation:
Partial Requirements Capacity =Capacity Billing Loads –SRMPA Eligible Capacity Where:
"Capacity Billing Loads" means, for such calendar month, a quantity of capacity (expressed in MW) equal to the sum of the "Billing Loads" (determined in accordance with Section VI.A of the HLFS Tariff) of the Nelson IP Retail Customers under the Nelson IP Retail Contracts at the Delivery Points for such calendar month, in each case adjusted upward by (i) 1.5% for transformation losses where applicable as determined by the HLFS Tariff, (ii) 3% for transmission losses and (iii) 16.8% for reserves.
"SRMPA Eligible Capacity" means, for such calendar month, the lesser of (i) the SRMPA Monthly Capacity Limit for such calendar month and (ii) the SRMPA Delivered Capacity for such calendar month.
Where:
"SRMPA Monthly Capacity Limit" means, for such calendar month, the capacity (expressed in MW) set forth in Exhibit E for such calendar month.
"SRMPA Delivered Capacity" means, for such calendar month, the capacity (expressed in MW) calculated in accordance with the following formula: SRMPA Delivered Capacity = Aggregate SRMPA Delivered Energy/( OPH * 0.8) Where:
"Aggregate SRMPA Delivered Energy" means the SRMPA Delivered Energy for the On-Peak Hours of such calendar month and the On-Peak Hours of the eleven (11) calendar months immediately preceding such calendar month.
"OPH" means the aggregate number of On-Peak Hours during such calendar month and the eleven (11) calendar months immediately preceding such calendar month.
"On-Peak Hours" means, for each day, the sixteen (16) hour period beginning at 6:00 a.m. CPT on such day and ending at 10:00 p.m. CPT on such day. Provided that, during the first eleven (11) calendar months of the Delivery Period the Aggregate SRMPA Delivered Energy and the OPH shall be calculated based on the actual number of calendar months that have elapsed since the Delivery Period Commencement Date rather than eleven (11) calendar months immediately preceding such month.
Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge. Each calendar month during the Delivery Period, the charge for Partial Requirements Capacity (the "Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge") shall be determined in accordance with the following formula:
Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge =Partial Requirements Capacity *Partial Requirements Capacity Rate Where: "Partial Requirements Capacity" means, for such calendar month, the Partial Requirements Capacity for such calendar month determined in accordance with Section 3.1.
"Partial Requirements Capacity Rate" means, for such calendar month, the rate per MW of Partial Requirements Capacity determined pursuant to Exhibit B, which may be adjusted from time to time as contemplated by Article 6.
Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Section 3.2, if for any consecutive three (3) month period during any calendar year during the Delivery Term the Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge for each such month exceeds the Maximum Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge for each such month, the Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge for each remaining month in such calendar year shall not exceed the Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge Cap for such month.
Where: "Maximum Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge" means, for each month, the product of (i) the HLFS Capacity Rate for such month, (ii) the Partial Requirements Capacity for such month and (iii) 1.10.
"Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charge Cap" means, for each month, the product of (i) the HLFS Capacity Rate for such month and (ii) the Partial Requirements Capacity for such month.
Maximum Annual Partial Requirements Capacity Charge. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, for each calendar year during the Delivery Period, the sum of the Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charges during such calendar year shall not exceed an amount equal to the charges (excluding any "Fuel Adjustment" charges) that would have been payable by SRMPA during such calendar year had SRMPA taken service under the HLFS Tariff instead of this Agreement (the "Maximum Annual Partial Requirements Capacity Charge"). In calculating the Maximum Annual Partial Requirements Capacity Charge for such calendar year, the billing demands for each month of such calendar year shall be equal to the Partial Requirements Capacity for such month and the hourly energy component of each hour of such calendar year shall be equal to the sum of the Partial Requirements Energy for such hour and the SRMPA Substitute Energy for such hour. If in any calendar year the sum of the Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charges paid by SRMPA under this Agreement during such calendar year exceeds the Maximum Annual Partial Requirements Capacity Charge for such calendar year (such excess, the "SRMPA Overpayment"), EGSL shall refund such SRMPA Overpayment to SRMPA by providing SRMPA a credit against the Monthly Partial Requirements Capacity Charges for each calendar month of the immediately succeeding calendar year until such refund obligation has been satisfied. If any portion of a SRMPA Overpayment shall remain outstanding as of the termination of this Agreement, EGSL shall pay such amount to SRMPA within thirty (30) days of the termination of this Agreement. PARTIAL REQUIREMENTS ENERGY Partial Requirements Energy. During each hour of the Delivery Period, EGSL shall sell and deliver, or cause to be delivered, and SRMPA shall purchase and receive, energy at the Delivery Points equal to the Partial Requirements Energy determined in accordance with the following calculation: Partial Requirements Energy =Consumed Energy –SRMPA Delivered Energy Where: "Consumed Energy" means, for such hour, a quantity of energy (expressed in MWh) equal to the sum of energy delivered to the Nelson IP Retail Customers at the Delivery Points adjusted for losses calculated pursuant to Section III of the HLFS Tariff.
"SRMPA Delivered Energy" means, for such hour, the sum of (i) the SRMPA Network Resource Energy for such hour and (ii) the SRMPA Substitute Energy for such hour.
Monthly Partial Requirements Energy Charge. Each calendar month during the Delivery Period, the charge for Partial Requirements Energy (the "Monthly Partial Requirements Energy Charge") shall be determined in accordance with the following formula: Monthly Partial Requirements Energy Charge =(?Partial Requirements Energy (for each hour of such calendar month)) *Partial Requirements Energy Rate Where: "Partial Requirements Energy" has the meaning set forth in Section 4.1.
"Partial Requirements Energy Rate" means, for such calendar month, a rate per MWh equal to the "Energy Charge" for such calendar month determined pursuant to Exhibit C, increased or decreased, as applicable, by the "Fuel and Purchased Economic Power Adjustment Factor" for such calendar month determined pursuant to Exhibit C, each as may be adjusted from time to time as contemplated in Article 6.
SRMPA ENERGY DELIVERIES SRMPA Delivered Energy. During each hour of the Delivery Period, SRMPA may, but shall have no obligation to, deliver, or cause to be delivered, SRMPA Delivered Energy to the Entergy Transmission System in an amount equal to or less than the combined loads of the Nelson IP Customers in such hour, for the purpose of satisfying such loads. Any such SRMPA Delivered Energy shall be deemed received by the Nelson IP Customers when delivered to the Entergy Transmission System. SRMPA Network Resource Availability. ENTERGY GULF STATES LOUISIANA, L.L.C.
Market-Based Rate Tariff
1. Availability. Entergy Gulf States Louisiana, L.L.C. (“Seller”), may make available under this Tariff wholesale energy, capacity, and ancillary services as follows:
a. Electric Capacity and Energy: Seller may sell electric energy and capacity from time to time at rates, terms and conditions established by agreement with the purchaser subject to the terms and conditions set forth in in this Tariff. All such transactions shall be voluntary.
b. Ancillary Services: The ancillary services that Seller may make available under this Tariff for purchase for resale are as follows:
i. RTO/ISO specific:
1. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
2. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
3. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
4. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
5. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO.
ii. Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Energy Imbalance Service, Spinning Reserves, and Supplemental Reserves. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier; and (3) sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers.
2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services Seller, to the extent not otherwise subject to another tariff or rate schedule on file with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“Commission”).
3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Duration. This Tariff shall continue in effect until terminated or changed and such termination or change becomes effective in accordance with any applicable regulatory requirements.
5. Modifications. Seller may unilaterally apply under Federal Power Act Section 205 and the regulations promulgated thereunder to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this Tariff.
6. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions of sales shall be established by agreement between purchaser and Seller.
7. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller’s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
8. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority.
Exemptions. By order issued September 29, 2011, Entergy Services, Inc., 136 FERC ¶ 61,218 (2011), the Commission conditionally granted limited waivers of the separation of functions and information sharing provisions in sections 35.39(c)(2)(i) and 35.39(d)(1) of the Commission’s regulations with respect to (a) shared fuel procurement and outage scheduling operations at two fossil generating units co-owned by certain Entergy Operating Companies and certain of their market-regulated power sales affiliates and (b) shared fuel procurement and outage scheduling operations for nuclear plants owned, respectively, by certain Entergy Operating Companies and certain market-regulated power sales affiliates. Id. at PP 22, 26, 29.
9. Affiliate Authorizations. Under the Entergy System Agreement, a jurisdictional rate schedule on file with the Commission, the Entergy Operating Companies exchange energy pursuant to Service Schedule MSS-3. Moreover, in Docket No. ER03-753, the Commission authorized the Entergy Operating Companies to engage in affiliate transactions pursuant to Service Schedule MSS-4 of the Entergy System Agreement. See Entergy Services, Inc., 111 FERC ¶ 61,035 (2005).
10. Effective Date. This Tariff is effective upon the date authorized by the Commission.
11. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Northeast, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions and a Category 2 seller in the Central region, as the terms “Category 1” and “Category 2” are defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a).

Nelson STATION, Coal Unit #6 Marketing Agreement
This Nelson Station, Coal Unit #6 Marketing Agreement (“Agreement”) is made as of October 14, 2013 (“Execution Date”), by and among Entergy Gulf States Louisiana, L.L.C. (“EGSL”), Entergy Texas, Inc., East Texas Electric Cooperative, Inc. (“ETEC”), Sam Rayburn G&T, Inc. (“SRG&T”), and EAM Nelson Holding, L.L.C. (collectively, the “Parties” and individually, a “Party”).
WHEREAS, the Parties are co-owners in Roy S. Nelson Station, Coal Unit #6 (“JOU”) pursuant to the Joint Ownership Participation and Operating Agreement, Nelson Station, Coal Unit #6 by and among the Parties (as amended, “Operating Agreement”); WHEREAS, the Parties are parties to the Operating Agreement whereby EGSL is given sole and plenary authority for the management, control, operation and maintenance of the JOU and is authorized to act as agent in all activities in connection with participants’ interest in the JOU on behalf of the other owners of the JOU; WHEREAS, the Parties anticipate participation in the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) energy and ancillary services market (“MISO Market”) beginning on or near December 19, 2013; and WHEREAS, the Parties wish to coordinate their participation in the MISO Market with respect to the JOU so as to maximize the value of the JOU and to share in the value of the JOU in proportion to their ownership share of the JOU, with no preference to any one owner; NOW, THEREFORE, the Parties agree as follows: TERM
Subject to Section 9.4 and Article 8, this Agreement will be in effect from the Execution Date until the first day on which the JOU is retired from commercial service or such other date as may be agreed upon by all the Parties (“Term”). The portion of the Term prior to participation in the MISO Market (or any successor market that is a part of the MISO Market) is designated as the “Preparation Period.” The portion of the Term beginning with entry into the MISO Market is designated as the “Participation Period.”
EFFECT ON OTHER AGREEMENTS Upon commencement of the Participation Period, any provision in this Agreement that contradicts, modifies, or otherwise alters any provision in the Operating Agreement shall be deemed to replace or override such provision of the Operating Agreement to the extent of such contradiction, modification, or alteration, including, without limitation, the following provisions of the Operating Agreement: Operating AgreementSection 8.4 – Sharing of Costs of OperationsExhibit D – Acknowledgement of Ownership & Confirmation of Ownership The Parties hereby confirm that any provision in the Operating Agreement that does not contradict, modify, or otherwise alter a provision in this Agreement shall remain in full force and effect on and subject to the terms set forth therein.
MARKET COMMITTEE Formation and Duties. There shall be a “Market Committee” composed of representatives of the Parties. Subject to the limitations in this Article 3, it shall generally be the duty of the Market Committee to review the market results and future market plans for the JOU, including the offer methodology of the Single Asset Approach set forth in Article 5 and Appendix A and MISO settlements, payments, and related charges in respect of the JOU. The Market Committee shall have authority to approve or direct modification of the offer methodology prepared by EGSL for the Single Asset Approach set forth in Article 5 and Appendix A, including the determination of incremental cost for the JOU. The Market Committee shall have authority to approve or direct modification of procedures developed by EGSL for unit commitment and dispatch of the JOU. The Market Committee shall have authority to develop procedures for establishing and modifying the offer adjustment applicable to the Single Asset Approach set forth in Appendix A. The Market Committee and its members shall have access to all operational, cost and settlement data that pertain to the JOU’s participation in the MISO Market. Restriction on Authority. The Market Committee shall have no authority to alter, amend, or revise the express provisions of this Agreement. Membership. The Market Committee shall be composed of one (1) representative of each of the Parties. The representative of EGSL to the Market Committee shall serve as Chairman. Each Party shall evidence its appointment of its representative and an alternate representative to the Market Committee by written notice from the chief executive of the Party to the other Parties. Each representative (including the alternate representative when serving as the representative) appointed by a Party hereunder shall have the authority to act for and obligate the Party it represents, as provided herein. At any time that any of the Parties changes its representative or designated alternate to the Market Committee, notice of such change shall be provided to all Parties by written notice to the members of the Market Committee. Each Party assumes full responsibility for the personal expenses of its representative to the Market Committee. Meetings. The Market Committee shall schedule an initial meeting of the Market Committee no later than 60 days after the Execution Date and thereafter such other meetings as it deems appropriate. Any one (1) member of the Market Committee may call a meeting of the Market Committee by providing reasonable notice thereof to the other Parties. Meeting minutes shall be prepared by the Chairman and distributed for review and approval within two weeks of each meeting. Voting. Each Party that utilizes the Single Asset Approach, as defined in Section 5.1 and as set forth in Article 5 and Appendix A, shall have the right to vote on matters before the Market Committee through the exercise of its Voting Rights. Parties that utilize the Individual Approach, as defined in Section 5.1 and as set forth in Article 5 and Appendix B, shall not have the right to vote on matters before the Market Committee and thus shall not possess any Voting Rights, but its representative (or, in his or her absence, alternate representative) may attend Market Committee meetings. The “Voting Rights” of a Party with Voting Rights shall be one vote for each ownership interest percentage of such Party in the JOU. For the avoidance of doubt, a Party’s Voting Rights includes a fractional vote if such Party has an ownership interest percentage that is not in a whole number. A Party’s Voting Rights shall be exercised exclusively by its designated representative to the Market Committee (or, in his or her absence, alternate representative or, subject to Section 3.5.1, proxy). Subject to the other terms of this Agreement, the Market Committee may take votes on matters that apply to the JOU and are within the authority of the Market Committee. A quorum of at least 50% of the Parties with Voting Rights must be represented at a Market Committee meeting in order for the Market Committee to take any action at such meeting. Parties may be represented at a Market Committee meeting by a representative (or, in his or her absence, alternate representative) appointed pursuant to Section 3.3, either in person or by telephone, electronic interactive medium or proxy. A Party represented by proxy at a Market Committee meeting shall provide written or electronic notice thereof to all other Parties prior to the start of such Market Committee meeting. Each Party shall use good faith efforts to be represented at each meeting of the Market Committee. Subject to Section 3.5.1 and Section 3.5.3, any matter properly before and to be decided by the Market Committee shall be decided by the majority of all votes cast on such matter by the representatives (or, if applicable, alternate representatives) of the Parties that have Voting Rights and are not then in default under any provision of this Agreement. Authorization by the Market Committee of a change to the floor or the ceiling of the offer band established in Section 4 of Appendix A requires the approval of at least 75% of the Market Committee members that possess Voting Rights. Right to Information. EGSL shall make available to the Market Committee all information submitted to MISO, information necessary to perform its duties set forth in Section 3.1, information required to verify that EGSL has submitted offers in accordance with the offer methodology adopted pursuant to Section 3.1.1, and, upon the direction of the Market Committee, any other information required to verify settlements with the MISO Market. Notwithstanding the foregoing, other than billing information, EGSL’s obligation to provide information to the Market Committee shall be limited to information reasonably requested that cannot otherwise be readily obtained in comparable form. Relationship to Other Committees. In complying with the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the Market Committee shall at all times act independently of any other committees established pursuant to any other agreements between or among any of the Parties. The Co-owners’ Committee established in the Operating Agreement shall continue its roles and responsibilities as defined therein.
EGSL OBLIGATIONS 4.1 General Obligations. Throughout the Term, EGSL shall perform the following responsibilities: manage this Agreement and coordinate Market Committee activities; submit offers to the MISO Market for Parties utilizing the Single Asset Approach; maintain systems that enable the certification(s) necessary to make ancillary service offers and the deployment of such ancillary services as directed by MISO for those Parties utilizing the Single Asset Approach; ensure that systems, processes and procedures are in place to manage the flow of information to and from Parties that use the Individual Approach and to accept deployment directions and determine energy allocations; manage settlements with MISO for the JOU, to the extent consistent with Appendix A and Appendix B, including the resolution of billing disputes; respond to data requests from MISO or the MISO market monitor regarding JOU operations; respond to inquiries of the Parties related to this Agreement; provide settlement information in a timely manner to Parties; maintain proper registration of the JOU in the MISO Market and communications with the MISO Market; facilitate a Party’s implementation of the Individual Approach, if selected; and for each Party operating under the Single Asset Approach, transfer to such Party (or its designated representative), after EGSL’s receipt thereof, such Party’s share, based on its ownership interest in the JOU, of the capacity credits (e.g., zonal resource credits), if any, granted by MISO from time to time with respect to the JOU. 4.2 Offer Methodology. If the Market Committee directs EGSL to propose to the Market Committee modifications to the then-current offer methodology approved by the Market Committee, EGSL shall endeavor to propose such modifications in accordance with the Market Committee’s directions.
OFFERS OF ENERGY AND ANCILLARY SERVICES
Offerings of Energy and Ancillary Services. As described more fully in this Article 5 and in Appendices A and B, Parties may offer their respective shares of energy and ancillary services from the JOU into the MISO Market on either a combined basis through EGSL (“Single Asset Approach”) or on an individual basis (“Individual Approach”). Single Asset Approach. EGSL shall have exclusive responsibility to submit offers of energy and ancillary services from the JOU into both the day-ahead and real-time MISO Market on behalf of those Parties using the Single Asset Approach (the “SAA Parties”). Submission of energy and ancillary services from the JOU into the MISO Market pursuant to the Single Asset Approach shall occur pursuant to procedures and a documented offer methodology to approximate the incremental cost of producing energy and ancillary services from the JOU adopted by the Market Committee, subject to Section 3.1.3 hereto and Section 4 of Appendix A. EGSL shall develop an offer methodology to be used for offering energy and ancillary services from the JOU into the MISO Market pursuant to the Single Asset Approach. The offer methodology developed by EGSL shall adhere to the principles outlined in Appendix A and shall be submitted by EGSL to the Market Committee for approval pursuant to Section 3.1.1. EGSL shall endeavor to provide its initial proposed offer methodology for the Single Asset Approach to the Market Committee for the review and possible approval of the Market Committee no later than 30 days prior to the expected start of the Participation Period (as of the date of this Agreement, December 19, 2013). EGSL shall develop procedures for unit commitment and dispatch of the JOU applicable to the Single Asset Approach and submit such procedures to the Market Committee for approval pursuant to Section 3.1.2. In the event that a Party disputes the Market Committee’s disposition of an issue that arises in connection with EGSL’s development or application of an offer methodology adopted by the Market Committee, such disputes shall be resolved pursuant to Article 7. EGSL shall settle all charges and payments, including MISO administrative charges, applicable to the JOU. Without limiting Section 6.3.3, each Party using the Single Asset Approach will receive its ownership percentage of the Net Benefits, as defined in Section 6.3.2, from the JOU on a monthly basis, as described in Article 6. The fuel-related costs used to determine each Party’s Net Benefits for the settlement period, as provided for in this Section 5.2.3 and in Article 6, will be based on actual costs. Any Party that desires to submit energy and ancillary services offers into the MISO Market through the Single Asset Approach shall consent and agree that EGSL shall act as agent on that Party’s behalf solely for the purpose of submitting energy and ancillary services offers into the MISO Market. Such consent and agreement shall be documented through execution of the pro forma agency agreement attached as Appendix C. EGSL is not authorized to act, and affirmatively rejects any characterization, as agent for any Party in any capacity other than that specifically set forth in this Section 5.2.4 and in Appendix C (to the extent applicable to the Joint Asset Approach) and, in agreeing to act as agent to the limited extent provided herein and therein, is relying on, among other provisions of this Agreement and the Operating Agreement, Sections 5.2.9, 9.1, 9.6, 9.7, and 9.9 herein. FEES AND PAYMENTS Monthly Marketing Fee. For any month in the Participation Period, each Party that is an SAA Party in such month shall pay to EGSL an amount equal to (a) such Party’s ownership percentage of the JOU in such month multiplied by (b) the Monthly Marketing Fee. The “Monthly Marketing Fee” means the aggregate monthly fee charged to the SAA Parties by EGSL for the performance of services under this Agreement. For each month through the 2018 calendar year, the Monthly Marketing Fee shall equal the Base Marketing Fee. The “Base Marketing Fee” shall equal $41,667. For each month after the 2018 calendar year, the Monthly Marketing Fee shall equal (i) the Base Marketing Fee multiplied by (ii) the sum of {1 + [(PPIB2 – PPIB1)/PPIB1]}. For this purpose, (A) “PPIB” means the average of (1) the Producer Price Index for Electric Power Generation, Primary Products (PCU221110221110P) and (2) the Producer Price Index for Electric Bulk Power Transmission and Control, Primary Products (PCU221121221121P), each as published by the United States Bureau of Labor Statistics (or if either such index shall cease to be published, such other index as may be reasonably agreed by the Parties), for the applicable month; (B) “PPIB1” means the PPIB in effect as of December 2018; and (C) “PPIB2” means the PPIB in effect for the month in respect of which the applicable Monthly Marketing Fee is due (e.g., if the Monthly Marketing Fee is due in respect of July 2019, PPIB2 would be the PPIB in effect for July 2019). For the avoidance of doubt, the Monthly Marketing Fee is not intended to include, and does not include, or serve, in whole or in part, as compensation or payment for, without limitation, Costs of Operation, as defined in the Operating Agreement, and MISO-related costs and expenses.
Individual Approach Invoices and Payments. EGSL shall provide a monthly invoice (“Invoice”) to each Party that uses the Individual Approach by the 15th business day of each calendar month (or on such other schedule as is mutually agreed on by EGSL and such Party). The Invoice for a Party using the Individual Approach will include: (i) the energy generated and allocated to the invoiced Party for the preceding month; (ii) the fuel cost calculation for fuel during the preceding month and allocated to the invoiced Party; (iii) any costs assessed by MISO to EGSL and allocated to the invoiced Party; and (iv) the total amount (in dollars) to be paid by the invoiced Party to EGSL for (a) the reimbursable costs described in Section 6 of Appendix B, incurred by EGSL in the preceding month and allocated to the invoiced Party, (b) the fuel costs incurred during the preceding month and allocated to the invoiced Party, (c) the MISO-related costs incurred during the preceding month and allocated to the invoiced Party, and (d) any other outstanding debit or cost allocated to and payable by the invoiced Party to EGSL in connection with this Agreement (net of any outstanding credit or payment allocated to and due and owed by EGSL to the invoiced Party in connection with this Agreement). Each Invoice received by a Party shall be paid in U.S. Dollars by wire transfer, check, or ACH payment delivered to EGSL within 15 days of the date of the Invoice (“Due Date”). If the Due Date for an Invoice is on a weekend or a bank holiday, payment for such Invoice will be due the next following business day. Late payments shall accrue interest at a per annum rate equal to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) electric interest rate applicable at the time interest is being accrued. Notwithstanding the above, if a good faith dispute arises between EGSL and another Party over any amount due under an Invoice, then the disputing Party will pay the Invoice on or before the applicable Due Date and both Parties will continue to perform their obligations under this Agreement during such dispute. EGSL agrees to provide the disputing Party documentation on which EGSL relied in validating and verifying a charge assessed in the Invoice and disputed by the disputing Party. Upon determination of the correct amount, EGSL will remit any amount due to the disputing Party promptly (but in any event within five (5) business days of resolution of the dispute) after such determination, with interest calculated at the interest rate provided in Section 6.2.1 from the applicable Due Date to the date the payment or refund is made. For any good faith dispute remaining after both Parties perform in accordance with the foregoing provisions of this Article 6, resolution of any such remaining good faith dispute shall be governed by Article 7. Single Asset Approach Payments. On a monthly basis, EGSL shall provide payment for Net Benefits to each Party that uses the Single Asset Approach by the 15th business day of each calendar month (or on such other schedule as is mutually agreed on by EGSL and such Party(ies)). With respect to any month, the “Net Benefit” for a Party is defined as the net of: (i) the sum of (a) amount of monies received from MISO for such month attributable to the ownership interest percentage of such Party in the JOU plus (b) any other outstanding credit or payment allocated to and due and owed by EGSL to the invoiced Party in connection with this Agreement, offset by (ii) the sum of (a) the total amount (in dollars) of the Monthly Marketing Fee allocated to such Party for such month as set forth in Section 6.1, (b) the fuel costs (in dollars) allocated to such Party for such month, (c) any MISO-related costs (in dollars) incurred during the preceding month and allocated to such Party, (d) any amount credited or paid to such Party for the preceding month as a result of implementation of the process described in Section 6.3.3, and (e) any other outstanding debit or cost allocated to and payable by the invoiced Party to EGSL in connection with this Agreement. In the event that the Net Benefit for a Party in a month is negative (that is, the amount of monies for such Party in such month under clause (i) above is less than the offset for such Party in such month determined under clause (ii) above), EGSL shall provide an Invoice to such Party setting forth the net costs due from such Party to EGSL (that is, the negative Net Benefit). Such Invoice shall be paid in accordance with the provisions of Sections 6.2.1 and 6.2.2. EGSL shall use good faith efforts to develop and implement, on or before the later of (a) June 30, 2014 or (b) six (6) months after the first day of the Participation Period, a process that provides for the payment to each SAA Party of its allocated share of any ordinary course weekly financial settlement paid to EGSL as the SAA Market Participant by MISO with respect to the portion of the JOU owned by the SAA Parties within seven (7) Business Days after EGSL’s receipt of such financial settlement. Unless otherwise agreed to by the Disputing Parties, the mediation of the Dispute shall be concluded within 90 days from the date of notice of the request for mediation thereof made in accordance with Section 7.3. Admissibility. All offers, promises, conduct and statements, whether oral or written, made in connection with or during the mediation by any of the Disputing Parties, their agents, representatives, employees, experts and attorneys, and by the Mediator or any of the Mediator’s agents, representatives and employees, will not be subject to discovery and will be confidential, privileged and inadmissible for any purpose, including impeachment, in any arbitration or other proceeding between, among or involving the Disputing Parties, or any of them; provided, however, that evidence that is otherwise admissible or discoverable will not be rendered inadmissible or non-discoverable as a result of its appearance or use in such mediation. Appendix A Single Asset Approach
1. PURPOSE. The purpose of this Appendix A is to provide detail regarding a mechanism through which Parties may offer their respective shares of energy and ancillary services from the JOU into the MISO Market on a combined basis through EGSL (i.e., Single Asset Approach). 2. OFFER METHODOLOGY. The methodology to be developed by EGSL shall allow for offers that approximate the incremental cost of producing energy and ancillary services and that utilize the most current heat rate curve information for the JOU, the best estimate for the actual incremental cost of delivered coal that would be purchased and delivered due to incremental generation at the JOU, the current market price of emission allowances, the best available estimate for variable operation and maintenance expenses for the JOU, and any incremental cost associated with future operational, legal, and regulatory rules and requirements. 3. OFFER DATA. Offer data submitted into the MISO Market pursuant to Section 5.2.2 of the Agreement will include unit parameters, unit limits, unit status, and production cost information for the JOU. 4. OFFER ADJUSTMENT. Each offer made under the Single Asset Approach shall include an adjustment to the price of the offer to increase the probability of the full and complete recovery of all marginal costs related to the JOU in periods where offers from the JOU establish the locational marginal price. Without limiting Section 3.1.3 of the Agreement, EGSL will establish the initial offer adjustment to be applied to offers and may modify the offer adjustment from time to time in its sole discretion; provided, however, that, with respect to any offer, the offer adjustment may not be (i) less than two percent (2%) of the projected incremental cost to operate the JOU during the period of time in which the offer applies or (ii) more than ten percent (10%) of such cost, unless (a) exclusively with respect to clause (i), the Market Committee approves, pursuant to Section 3.5.3 of the Agreement, an offer adjustment that is lower than two percent (2%) of such cost or (b) exclusively with respect to clause (ii), the Market Committee approves, pursuant to Section 3.5.3 of the Agreement, an offer adjustment that is higher than ten percent (10%) of such cost, in which case, for both clause (a) and (b), the offer adjustment may not be outside of the range approved by the Market Committee (subject to the terms of such Market Committee approval). Notwithstanding anything to the contrary, no term of this Appendix A or the Agreement is intended to require, and no authorization of the Market Committee shall require, EGSL to submit an offer into the MISO Market that EGSL knows would be, or has determined in good faith may be interpreted to be, subject to mitigation by the independent market monitor for MISO or in violation of applicable MISO rules, tariffs, policies, protocols, procedures or requirements, applicable laws or the terms of this Agreement.
Appendix B Individual Offer Approach
PURPOSE. The purpose of this Appendix B is to provide a general construct for the implementation of a JOU arrangement that would allow one or more owners of the JOU to make offers into the MISO Market on an individual basis (i.e., Individual Offer Approach). The Parties recognize that the details of implementing this approach are complex and dependent on, among other things, the details of the MISO Market design that are in place at the time of implementation, the capabilities of the hardware and software systems of the owners and their service providers, and the capabilities of the hardware and software systems of EGSL and its service providers. DEFINITIONS. Single Asset JOU Group (“SAJG”) – The group of owners, represented by EGSL, that makes offers to the MISO Market on a combined basis as defined in Article 5 and Appendix A of the Agreement. Individual Offering Owner (“IOO”) – An owner that is not participating in the SAJG and is making offers to MISO on an individual basis. GENERAL RESPONSIBILITIES. Each IOO will be responsible for representing its share of the JOU in the MISO Market independently of the other ownership shares. Such representation includes, without limitation, registration, resource plans, offers, deployment, settlement, transmission service and any other related market activities. EGSL, as the representative of the SAJG, will continue to be responsible for representing the portions of the JOU belonging to the SAJG participants in the MISO Market. The SAJG and each IOO commit to offer its share of the JOU to the MISO Market anytime the JOU is available to generate. The methodology to address the allocation of costs associated with the minimum run level of the JOU when only a portion of the JOU has been selected to operate in the MISO Market shall be developed as part of the implementation process under Section 6, below. It will be each IOO’s responsibility to keep MISO informed of the status of its portion of the JOU, including, without limitation, notification of de-rates and outages. It will be each IOO’s responsibility to receive deployment instructions with respect to its portion of the JOU from the MISO Market for each market interval and deliver them to EGSL on a timeframe suitable for market operation, or make other arrangements to effect the same result such that EGSL can respond to market operation. If an IOO wishes to offer regulation reserves, spinning reserves and/or operating reserves into the MISO Market, the IOO must gain certification for such services from the MISO Market and develop the system and processes needed to communicate ancillary serve deployment direction to EGSL. An IOO may not take any action that will prohibit the SAJG from gaining certification to offer regulation reserves, spinning reserves and/or supplemental reserves from the portion of the JOU that is a part of the SAJG or obstruct in any way the SAJG from making offers for regulation reserve, spinning reserve and/or supplemental reserve into the MISO Market. EGSL RESPONSIBILITIES. EGSL will provide JOU-related information needed for each IOO to interface with the MISO Market. The details of the information needed will be developed in the detailed design phase of implementation based on the current MISO Market design. EGSL will provide each IOO full access to the records, outage data, fuels and fuel-related costs, variable O&M/start cost calculations, and other information related to the costs and operation of the JOU so that the IOO can bid its share of the JOU into the MISO Market in a manner that satisfies its obligations as a Market Participant under the MISO Open Access Transmission, Energy and Operating Reserve Markets Tariff and MISO Market rules. If not provided directly by MISO to the IOO, EGSL will provide an IOO data in order for it to shadow settle its share of the JOU in real-time; this data shall include all information provided to or made available by MISO, including all five-minute data. EGSL will receive and check the deployment instructions from each IOO to ensure consistency with the then-current physical capabilities of the JOU and the IOO’s share of those physical capabilities. EGSL will combine the deployment instructions from the IOOs with the deployment instructions for the SAJG to develop a target output for the JOU and will dispatch the JOU to attempt to meet such target output. In the event no deployment instruction for an interval is received from an IOO in time for inclusion in the target output calculation, EGSL will use the last received deployment instruction from that IOO. EGSL will perform the allocation process for actual generation from the JOU described below. The total MW allocated to each IOO will be electronically transmitted to the IOOs immediately after the calculations for any interval have been completed, giving the IOOs real-time operational feedback of their asset’s performance. Each IOO will provide the same values to MISO. If EGSL submits to, or receives settlement information from, MISO or the MISO market monitor, EGSL will provide each IOO with all data provided to MISO or the MISO market monitor and the settlement data that EGSL receives from MISO or the MISO market monitor. ALLOCATION PROCESS. For each market interval, each IOO’s total allocation of JOU energy will be the sum of two components: the base allocation and the deviation allocation. The base allocation for each IOO will equal its requested deployment level (if any), as adjusted by EGSL as described in Section 4.4, above. The deviation allocation for each IOO will apply when there is a difference between the actual and target output of the entire JOU (the difference, which may be positive or negative, being the deviation MW) and will be calculated in accordance with the following rules: If there are deviation MW for an interval, the amount of deviation MW allocated to an IOO for such interval will be determined by multiplying (a) the deviation MW for such interval by (b) a factor equal to (i) the requested deployment MW of the applicable IOO for such interval divided by (ii) the aggregate owner-requested deployment MW of the JOU for such interval, each of clause (i) and (ii) as adjusted by EGSL in accordance with Section 4.4, above, subject to Section 5.2, below. Except as provided below, the deviation MW allocated to an IOO will be limited to those deviation MW that do not cause the combined base allocation and deviation allocation for an interval to exceed the maximum, or be below the minimum, permitted deployment MW of the IOO for such interval. Any deviation MW of an IOO that exceed the maximum, or are below the minimum, permitted deployment MW of the IOO for such interval will be allocated to the other IOOs (if any) in such interval. In the event that, after completion of the foregoing allocation process for such interval, any deviation MW have not been allocated to an IOO, then all such deviation MW shall be allocated to the owners of the JOU pro rata based on each owner’s requested deployment MW to the aggregate requested deployment MW. Implementation Process. After notification to EGSL and the other owners of the JOU that one or more owners will become an IOO pursuant to Section 5.3.2 of the Agreement, EGSL and the owner(s) that made such notification will work together to develop an implementation plan in accordance with the provisions of this Appendix B, including, without limitation, an implementation schedule, operating protocols and procedures, data flow diagrams, testing procedures, operator training procedures, settlement procedures, and plans for receiving any and all required certifications and approvals. All Parties will use reasonable efforts to support the process for developing a reasonable IOO implementation plan. EGSL will use reasonable commercial practices to accurately record the cost it incurs to (i) support the process for developing any IOO implementation plan and/or (ii) support the implementation and execution of any IOO implementation plan, including, without limitation, any cost it incurs in connection with registrations, offers, schedules, settling, coordination and other actions that it would not have incurred but for the implementation or execution (or attempted implementation or execution) of the IOO implementation plan. Each month EGSL will endeavor to charge the owners that are, or are working to become, IOOs for all such costs EGSL incurred for the prior month. If the Parties reach an impasse on any aspect of the design of the IOO implementation plan, then the Parties shall invoke the arbitration process as described in Section 7 herein (and not the arbitration process as described in Article 7 of the main body of the Agreement). The Parties agree that, in such event, the decision or outcome of the arbitration process as described in Section 7 herein will establish the disputed design aspects of the implementation plan for the Individual Offer Approach. IMPLEMENTATION PROCESS DISPUTES. In the event that EGSL and a Party seeking to become an IOO are unable to agree on the implementation plan described in Section 6 above, either EGSL or such Party may initiate arbitration with respect to the disputed matters by providing a notice of a demand for binding arbitration to the other. EGSL and such Party will cooperate with one another in selecting the arbitrator within 60 days after notice of the demand for arbitration. If they are unable to agree upon a mutually acceptable arbitrator, EGSL and such Party each shall appoint one arbitrator within 60 days after receipt of notice of demand. The two Party-appointed arbitrators shall appoint a third arbitrator within 30 days after their appointment. The third arbitrator shall act as chair of the panel. Except as provided in Section 7.3 below, the arbitration will be conducted by the arbitrator(s) in accordance with the Commercial Rules of the American Arbitration Association, as modified herein. Any dispute concerning the implementation plan for participation by a Party in the MISO Market as an IOO shall be subject to binding arbitration. Each Party to the dispute shall submit to the arbitrator(s) and exchange with the other, in accordance with a procedure to be established by the arbitrator(s), its proposal for the implementation plan to be applied. The arbitrator(s) shall be limited to awarding only one or the other of the proposals submitted and may not modify the proposals. The arbitration award shall be binding on the Parties to the arbitration for a period of five (5) years, after which a Party may seek to re-arbitrate the implementation plan methodology. SUBSEQUENT ELECTION. In the event that any Party elects to establish a pseudo-tie arrangement to move all or a portion of its ownership share of the JOU outside of the MISO Market, EGSL and that Party will negotiate in good faith to reach a mutually agreeable solution, setting forth the terms and conditions of offering energy and/or ancillary services outside of the MISO Market. Any such solution shall be set forth in a separate agreement. In the event the Parties are unable to reach agreement, the Parties may pursue arbitration on the terms provided in Section 7 of this Appendix B (substituting therein the pseudo-tie arrangement plan for IOO implementation plan and similar provisions where appropriate).

GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS FORWHOLESALE DISTRIBUTION SERVICEFROM AN ENTERGY OPERATING COMPANY This WDS Tariff sets forth the rates, terms, and conditions of service for an entity (“WDS Customer”) that requires Wholesale Distribution Service (“WDS” or “WDS Service”) over the Distribution Facilities of Entergy Arkansas, Inc., Entergy Gulf States Louisiana L.L.C., Entergy Louisiana, LLC, Entergy Mississippi, Inc., Entergy New Orleans, Inc., or Entergy Texas, Inc. (each such entity individually referred to herein as an Entergy Operating Company (“Entergy OC”)) in order to receive energy from or deliver energy to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc.’s (“MISO”) Transmission System. Eligibility The Entergy OC will provide WDS pursuant to the applicable rates, terms, and conditions contained in this WDS Tariff. This WDS Tariff is applicable for the transportation of capacity and energy that is (1) generated or purchased by a WDS Customer at a generation source and transported to the Transmission System using the Entergy OC’s Distribution Facilities, or (2) generated or purchased by a WDS Customer from generation sources and transported from the Transmission System to the WDS Customer’s Wholesale Load using the Entergy OC’s Distribution Facilities. WDS shall be provided between the Entergy OC’s interconnection with the Transmission System and the WDS Customer’s interconnection with the Entergy OC’s Distribution Facilities. Service hereunder shall not be available if the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) would be prohibited from ordering such service under Section 212(h) of the Federal Power Act. Definitions Capitalized terms not defined in this section have the same definition as the term in the MISO Tariff. Commencement Date: December 19, 2013. Commission: Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. Distribution Facilities: Those facilities used for the delivery of energy that are owned, controlled, and operated by the Entergy OC but that are not Transmission System facilities. Existing WDS Customer: A WDS Customer that took wholesale distribution service from an Entergy OC prior to the Commencement Date, including an entity that took bundled transmission and distribution service. New WDS Customer: A WDS Customer other than an Existing WDS Customer. Wholesale Distribution Load: End-use customers’ load that a WDS Customer serves, either directly or through its own wholesale customers, from distribution facilities that the WDS Customer owns or controls for which WDS is obtained under this WDS Tariff. Transmission Service Nothing in this WDS Tariff conveys a right to transmission service under the MISO Tariff. Customer shall separately obtain transmission service subject to the rates, terms and conditions of the MISO Tariff. Obtaining WDS Existing WDS Customers: Within ninety (90) days of the Commencement Date, an Existing WDS Customer will be provided, for signature, a Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement (in the form of Exhibit A) that reflects the applicable Distribution Service rates and charges, as calculated pursuant to Section 5. If the Existing Customer declines to execute the Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement, the Entergy OC will ask MISO to file such agreement unexecuted prior to the Commencement Date. New WDS Customers: A Customer that is not an Existing Customer may request WDS by providing the information identified below, which will constitute an Application. Applications shall be submitted by mail to Entergy Services, Inc. Interconnection Arrangements Administrator P.O. Box 61000 New Orleans, LA 70161. This method will provide a date-stamped record of the Application for establishing the priority of the Application. WDS Customer Name/Address/Contact Information. Requested Service Commencement Date. Indication as to whether WDS is being requested for generator(s), Wholesale Load(s), or both Wholesale Load(s) and generator(s). For generators, a copy of the Customer’s generator interconnection request or a copy of the generator’s interconnection agreement. For Wholesale Loads, a copy of the Customer’s Application for Network Service provided to the MISO under MISO Tariff § 29.2. Distribution Service Charge 5.1 Existing WDS Customers: The initial Distribution Service Charge for an Existing WDS Customer is the rate that such entity is paying for wholesale distribution service under its existing transmission service arrangements. If such rate is currently a formula rate, the Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement will fix that rate at the level in effect the day before the Commencement Date. Where an entity is charged a rate that includes both distribution and transmission components, only the distribution component will be assessed as the Distribution Service Charge. The Distribution Service Charge may be revised pursuant to Section 5.3. 5.2 New WDS Customers: For Customers not utilizing a Company’s Distribution Facilities prior to the Commencement Date, a monthly Distribution Service Charge will be determined as follows: 1. The specific Distribution Facilities serving the WDS Customer shall be determined on a direct assignment cost basis; 2. The Entergy OC’s gross investment in the directly assigned facilities, determined based on the proposed effective date of the Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement, as determined in (1) above shall be multiplied by 1.5% to determine the monthly Distribution Service Charge. 3. After the monthly Distribution Service Charge is accepted by the Commission and allowed to become effective, it will remain in place until a revision is accepted and allowed to become effective by the Commission. 5.3 Distribution Service Charge Revisions: The relevant Entergy OC may revise the Distribution Service Charge from time-to-time by making a filing with the Commission pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act. Generally, such revisions will be made when there are significant changes in the specific Distribution Facilities of the relevant Entergy OC used to provide WDS, which changes may be triggered by events such as the addition or removal of delivery points, among other reasons. 5.4 Loss Factors: The following loss factors shall be applied, as applicable, on a compounded basis to adjust for metered values of generation and load of the WDS Customer’s meter(s) on the Entergy OC’s Distribution System for all purposes under this WDS Tariff:
ServiceLoss FactorDistribution Transformation Service1.01Distribution Line Service1.02 However, lower loss factors shall be utilized for a Customer’s injections and withdrawals when the Customer satisfactorily demonstrates that the characteristics of the facilities warrant such an adjustment. Non-standard loss factors will be specified in the Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement. Wholesale Load Obligation to Provide Updated Specifications If a WDS Customer has one or more Wholesale Distribution Loads, it is obligated to provide to the relevant Entergy OC a copy of any updated specifications for Network Service within five (5) business days of providing such updated Specifications to the MISO. Such copy of the Specifications for Network Service may redact information that is relevant to any load not subject to a Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement with an Entergy OC. Force Majeure An Entergy OC or WDS Customer shall not be considered in default as to any obligation under this WDS Tariff if prevented from fulfilling the obligation due to an event of Force Majeure. However, if the relevant Entergy OC’s or WDS Customer’s performance under this WDS Tariff is hindered by an event of Force Majeure, it shall make all reasonable efforts to perform its obligations under this WDS Tariff. An event of Force Majeure means any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy, war, act of terrorism, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any curtailment, order, regulation or restriction imposed by governmental military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other cause beyond the relevant Entergy OC’s or WDS Customer’s control applying Good Utility Practice. Limitation of Damages In no event shall either the relevant Entergy OC or WDS Customer be liable under this WDS Tariff or under any cause of action related to the subject matter of this WDS Tariff, whether based on contract, warranty, tort (including negligence), strict liability, indemnity, or otherwise for any incidental, special, punitive or consequential damages including, but not limited to, loss of use, increased costs of purchased or replacement power, interest charges, inability to operate at full capacity, lost profits, or claims of WDS Customer’s customers or members. The relevant Entergy OC shall not be liable to the WDS Customer, its customers or members for damages caused by interruption of service, voltage or frequency variations, single phase to three phase lines, reversal of phase rotation, or carrier-current frequencies imposed by the relevant Entergy OC for system operations or equipment control except such as result from the failure of Entergy OC to exercise Good Utility Practice in furnishing the service. WDS Customer may install protective equipment if such occurrences might damage its apparatus. Billing, Payment, and Default Invoices, which will be calculated by Entergy Services, Inc. on behalf of the relevant Entergy OC and issued by the MISO, shall be paid by the WDS Customer in accordance with the MISO Tariff. In the event the WDS Customer fails, for any reason other than a billing dispute as described below, to make payment to MISO on or before the due date as described above, and such failure of payment is not corrected within thirty (30) calendar days after the MISO notifies the WDS Customer to cure such failure, a default by the WDS Customer shall be deemed to exist. Upon the occurrence of a default, the Entergy OC may initiate a proceeding with the Commission to terminate service but shall not terminate service until the Commission so approves any such request. In the event of a billing dispute between the Entergy OC or MISO and the WDS Customer relating to this Tariff, the Entergy OC will continue to provide service under the Service Agreement as long as the WDS Customer (i) continues to make all payments not in dispute, and (ii) pays into an independent escrow account the portion of the invoice in dispute, pending resolution of such dispute. If the WDS Customer fails to meet these two requirements for continuation of service, then the Entergy OC may provide notice to the WDS Customer of its intention to suspend service in sixty (60) days, in accordance with Commission policy. Assignment 10.1 Except as provided in Section 10.2, a Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement may be assigned by the WDS Customer, without the consent of the relevant Entergy OC, but with prior written notice, to any entity or entities in connection with a merger, consolidation, reorganization or other change in the organizational structure of the WDS Customer, provided that the surviving or successor entity(ies) agree(s), in writing, to assume the assigning WDS Customer’s obligations and duties under, and be bound by, the terms of this WDS Tariff and further satisfy one of the following criteria: (a) the assignee has an investment grade credit rating; (b) the obligations of the assignee are guaranteed by a parent with an investment grade credit rating; or (c) the assignment is being made in connection with a merger, consolidation or sale of substantially all the assignor’s assets to another party that has an investment grade credit rating at least equal to that of the assignor. 10.2 Notwithstanding Section 10.1, the WDS Customer shall have the right to pledge its Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement for financing purposes without the consent of the relevant Entergy OC. 10.3 A Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement may be assigned by the Entergy OC, without the consent of the WDS Customer, but with prior written notice, to any entity or entities in connection with a merger, consolidation, reorganization or other change in the organizational structure of the Entergy OC, provided that the surviving or successor entity(ies) agree(s), in writing, to assume the assigning Entergy OC’s obligations and duties under, and be bound by, the terms of this WDS Tariff, so long as the assignee has an investment grade credit rating or the obligations of the assignee are guaranteed by a parent with an investment grade credit rating. Regulatory Filings Nothing contained in this WDS Tariff shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of the Entergy OC to unilaterally make application to the Commission for a change in rates, terms and conditions, charges, classification of service, rule or regulation under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to the Commission’s rules and regulations promulgated thereunder. Nothing contained in this WDS Tariff shall be construed as affecting in any way the ability of any WDS Customer receiving service under this WDS Tariff to exercise its rights under the Federal Power Act, including Sections 205 and 206, and pursuant to the Commission’s rules and regulations promulgated thereunder.

THIRD AMENDED INTERIM AGREEMENT FOR CONTINUATION OF TRANSMISSION SERVICE ARRANGEMENTS FOR INDUSTRIAL PARTICIPANT LOAD This THIRD AMENDED INTERIM AGREEMENT FOR CONTINUATION OF TRANSMISSION SERVICE ARRANGEMENTS FOR INDUSTRIAL PARTICIPANT LOAD (“Agreement”) is made and entered into as of September 28, 2015, by and between SAM RAYBURN MUNICIPAL POWER AGENCY, a political subdivision of the State of Texas (“SRMPA”), and ENTERGY GULF STATES LOUISIANA, L.L.C., a limited liability company organized and existing under the laws of the State of Louisiana (“EGSL”) (each individually a “Party” or collectively the “Parties”). RECITALS WHEREAS, EGSL and the City of Jasper, Texas entered into an Amended and Restated Wholesale Power Service Agreement on June 30, 2010 (“WPSA”), under which EGSL was responsible for arranging for transmission service, including ancillary services, to the load at the delivery points specified in the WPSA (“Industrial Participant Load”); WHEREAS, pursuant to Section 5 of the WPSA, EGSL fulfilled that commitment by arranging for such transmission service pursuant to the Open Access Transmission Tariff administered by Entergy Services, Inc. (“ESI OATT”) and the Network Integration Transmission Service Agreement between ESI and the Entergy Operating Companies (“Entergy Operating Companies’ NITSA”); WHEREAS, the WPSA, including EGSL’s obligation to provide transmission service to the Industrial Participant Load, terminated effective on the “Delivery Period Commencement Date” as defined in the Agreement for Partial Requirements Wholesale Electric Service between EGSL and Sam Rayburn Municipal Power Agency dated August 1, 2011 (“2011 PRA”); WHEREAS, the 2011 PRA provides that SRMPA will obtain network customer status under the ESI OATT by entering into a network transmission service agreement (“SRMPA NITSA”); WHEREAS, pursuant to an Agency Agreement dated August 1, 2011 (“Agency Agreement”), EGSL was willing to serve as a transmission agent for SRMPA for purposes of obtaining network transmission service; WHEREAS, EGSL, on behalf of SRMPA as its agent, has applied for network integration transmission service seeking to designate as Network Resources the 2011 PRA as well as the Supplemental Requirements Power Supply Agreement between EWO Marketing, Inc. and SRMPA (“EWOM SRPSA”); WHEREAS, EGSL has been informed that (i) certain transmission system upgrades will be needed before the SRMPA NITSA can be made effective and (ii) such upgrades are not expected to be completed until 2015; WHEREAS, SRMPA requires transmission service to the Industrial Participant Load until such time as the SRMPA NITSA becomes effective; WHEREAS, the Parties executed that certain Interim Agreement for Continuation of Transmission Service Arrangements for Industrial Participant Load (“Original Agreement”) on October 26, 2011, for the purpose of enabling SRMPA to obtain such transmission service and filed the Original Agreement with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission on October 27, 2011, to become effective December 1, 2011, in accordance with its terms;
